    <div class="page-header">
        <p class="page-read-time">~ 20 MIN READ</p>
        <h1 class="page-title">THE LUMINARIUM</h1>
    </div>

    <div class="page-content">

        <!-- Intro -->
        <section class="luminarium-intro">
            <p>Three centuries after the fall, Earth is a graveyard of civilizations and a nursery for alien flora. Bizarre vegetation chokes the landscape in ribbons of puce and violet, exhaling poison into an atmosphere that grows less hospitable by the month. The mammals are gone&mdash;only insects, reptiles, and egg-layers endure. Humanity clings to existence in underground bunkers, lawless subterranean cities, and the fortified dome of Sid Mantelis, where an animistic religion called the Church of Life worships the beasts of a world that no longer exists.</p>
            <p>Into this wasteland, a prophecy has been spoken: <em class="prophecy">a child shall save the barren Earth.</em></p>
            <p>The Luminarium is a record of the people who carry that future on their shoulders&mdash;the fighters, the healers, the con artists, the prophets, and the unknowable strangers whose true natures will only reveal themselves when the time is right. These are their faces. These are the fragments of their stories that can be told without unraveling the threads still being woven.</p>
            <p>Welcome to the world of <strong>Metalstar</strong>.</p>
        </section>

        <div class="separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

        <!-- ==============================
             REGION 1: PROTOGAIA COLONY
             ============================== -->
        <section class="region-section">
            <h2 class="region-header">ProtoGaia Colony</h2>
            <p class="region-tagline">Where the old world sleeps, waiting to be reborn</p>
            <div class="region-image-wrapper">
                <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/region-protogaia.webp" alt="ProtoGaia Colony — A cryogenic preservation facility buried deep beneath the Earth's surface" loading="lazy">
            </div>
            <div class="region-text">
                <p>Deep beneath the surface, sealed behind doors that were never meant to be opened from the outside, lies Protogaia&mdash;a cryogenic preservation facility built in the final years before the Dark Epoch consumed civilization. Its architects believed they were preserving the best of humanity: its scientists, its soldiers, its DNA. Every species that ever walked, swam, or flew on Earth is cataloged in its vaults. Every breakthrough of the old world is archived in its databanks. Protogaia was humanity&rsquo;s insurance against extinction.</p>
                <p>The colonists who emerge from its chambers carry memories of a world that no longer exists&mdash;concert halls and green fields, oceans that moved and mammals that breathed. They wake into a landscape of alien flora and poisoned air, and nothing in their centuries-old training has prepared them for what Earth has become. But they bring something the wasteland desperately needs: knowledge. Technology. And the unshakable conviction that humanity was meant to endure.</p>
                <p>What Protogaia&rsquo;s creators stored in those vaults&mdash;and what they chose not to tell the colonists before putting them to sleep&mdash;may be the most dangerous secret left on Earth.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- SARAH GREENE -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">Sarah Greene</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">A cellist&rsquo;s memories in a fighter&rsquo;s body, caught between two lives she didn&rsquo;t choose</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/sarah-pose.webp" alt="Sarah Greene — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>Sarah carries the implanted memories of a woman who played Ravel&rsquo;s <em>Bol&eacute;ro</em> at the London Philharmonic&mdash;a woman who lived centuries ago, in a world of concert halls and green fields and mammals. She wakes into a reality of slave camps and alien flora and a sky the wrong color, and nothing in those borrowed memories has prepared her for any of it.</p>
                        <p>The granddaughter of Dr. Raymond Lemky, one of the most brilliant scientists of the old world, Sarah discovers that her lineage connects her to both humanity&rsquo;s greatest achievements and its most dangerous secrets. She doesn&rsquo;t understand this world at first. &ldquo;This is no kind of life,&rdquo; she says. But the wasteland has a way of remaking people, and Sarah transforms from a bewildered captive into something the rebels desperately need&mdash;someone willing to carry burdens that would break anyone else.</p>
                        <p>She notices the absence of music in this world the way a sailor notices the absence of the sea. It haunts her. It drives her. And it may, in the end, be the thing that saves her.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/sarah-outfit.webp" alt="Sarah Greene — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

            <div class="separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

            <!-- JOHN D'ARBY -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">John D&rsquo;arby</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">A Marine from the old world, reborn into a war he never trained for</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/john-pose.webp" alt="John D'arby — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>They call him Wachichu&mdash;&ldquo;white man&rdquo; in his ancestral tongue&mdash;a nickname that speaks to the contradiction at the heart of him. John is Native American, broad and towering, bronze-skinned and black-haired, a man who moves with startling lightness for his size. He grew up caught between two cultures on a reservation, outcast from both, raised by a mother who was a healer and a father who died too young. He joined the Marines because it was the one place where what you could do mattered more than where you came from.</p>
                        <p>Now he stands at the head of an army made from rubble&mdash;malnourished survivors of slave camps, untrained civilians, frightened children grown too fast. He shapes them into soldiers the way his grandfather would have: with patience, with stories, with the understanding that hope is the only weapon that never runs out of ammunition. &ldquo;An army travels on its belly,&rdquo; he says, and feeds his people well before asking them to die.</p>
                        <p>John carries wisdom from two traditions&mdash;military precision and the old stories his mother told by firelight, tales of wolves and hunters and the nature of things. He respects all life, even the creatures that terrorize humanity, seeing in them something familiar, something almost earthly. It is this quality&mdash;this refusal to reduce his enemy to mere monster&mdash;that makes him dangerous in ways a simple soldier could never be.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/john-outfit.webp" alt="John D'arby — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

            <div class="separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

            <!-- ROGER -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">ROGER</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">A physician whose abilities defy every known limit of human medicine</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/roger-pose.webp" alt="ROGER — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>ROGER presents himself as a doctor&mdash;but no doctor should be able to do what he does. His diagnostic capabilities border on the miraculous: he reads vital signs without instruments, detects poisons by proximity, and performs surgical procedures that should require an entire hospital wing. His knowledge of the old world&rsquo;s most advanced technology, particularly the biomagnetic research of Dr. Raymond Lemky, runs deeper than any living human&rsquo;s should.</p>
                        <p>Beneath his calm, philosophical demeanor lies a mind that processes consciousness itself as a puzzle worth solving. He speaks of the voices in the mind, the way identity is assembled from competing impulses, with the unsettling precision of someone describing machinery rather than mystery. His core conviction&mdash;<em>first, do no harm</em>&mdash;guides every decision, but his definition of harm accounts for variables no ordinary physician would consider.</p>
                        <p>Who is ROGER, really? Where did he come from? And why does he understand things about the human body&mdash;and the technologies that can reshape it&mdash;that no survivor of the apocalypse has any right to know? The answer, when it comes, will rewrite everything the survivors know about the world.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/roger-outfit.webp" alt="ROGER — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

        </section><!-- end region: ProtoGaia Colony -->

        <div class="region-separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

        <!-- ==============================
             REGION 2: THE WASTELAND & THE SPICE ROAD
             ============================== -->
        <section class="region-section">
            <h2 class="region-header">The Wasteland &amp; The Spice Road</h2>
            <p class="region-tagline">The space between survival and death, measured in footsteps</p>
            <div class="region-image-wrapper">
                <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/region-spiceroad.webp" alt="The Wasteland and The Spice Road — A vast sun-scorched landscape choked with alien flora" loading="lazy">
            </div>
            <div class="region-text">
                <p>Beyond the dome and the bunkers and the underground cities, the wasteland stretches&mdash;vast, sun-scorched, and unforgiving. The alien gardens have choked the landscape in ribbons of puce and violet, their roots weeping acid into soil where nothing native can take hold. The air grows thinner near the gardens, heavy with argon, and the mammals are gone. Only insects, reptiles, and egg-layers endure. The wasteland is not empty&mdash;it is full of ways to die.</p>
                <p>And yet, people cross it. Every day.</p>
                <p>The Spice Road is the black market lifeline that connects the scattered settlements of the 24th century&mdash;a network of traders, merchants, and smugglers who move food, medicine, and information across hundreds of miles on foot. There are no maps; the routes exist only in the minds of the Trade Masters who memorize them through dead reckoning and celestial navigation. When a Trade Master dies, the caravan is stranded. Spotters watch the sky for alien airships, and at the first sign of danger, an entire caravan of a hundred people drops to the ground and covers themselves in camouflage cloaks, becoming indistinguishable from the rocks and scrub around them. It is a life lived in constant motion, constant vigilance, and constant grief&mdash;but the Spice Road endures, because the last remaining pleasure in this world is food, and someone has to carry it.</p>
                <p>The wasteland shapes everyone who walks it. Some it breaks. Some it remakes into something harder, stranger, and more alive than they were before.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- JAYK -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">Jayk</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">A wasteland wanderer with twin blades and a past that someone erased</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/jayk-pose.webp" alt="Jayk — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>Jayk was born into the ruins, killing aliens by the age of eight, proficient with blades by thirteen. He carries a katana and a wakizashi gifted to him by a grateful swordsmith, and he moves through combat with the fluid grace of someone whose body remembers what his mind cannot. Because Jayk remembers nothing. Not his real name. Not where he came from. Not why.</p>
                        <p>The headaches are the only clue&mdash;sudden, blinding episodes that feel less like illness and more like something locked behind a door, hammering to get out. He thinks in animal metaphors without knowing why. He carries kindness like a weapon in a world that considers it a liability, trading his own sword to feed a stranger dying in the street. That single act of compassion will set in motion events no one could have predicted.</p>
                        <p>There are people in Sid Mantelis who recognize Jayk&rsquo;s face. People who know what he was before the memories were taken. When that truth surfaces, it will test every alliance he has built&mdash;and force the question of whether a man can truly become someone new, or whether the past always comes back to haunt them.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/jayk-outfit.webp" alt="Jayk — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

            <div class="separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

            <!-- ANJARI -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">Anjari</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">A trader who walks the Spice Road with burn scars and starlight</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/anjari-pose.webp" alt="Anjari — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>Anjari has been walking the Spice Road for two years, crossing the wastelands with trade caravans under cover of darkness, navigating by the stars she has memorized like a second language. She knows Sirius and Procyon, Orion&rsquo;s belt and the constellations of the hunting dogs, and she reads the night sky the way others read maps&mdash;fluently, instinctively, as though the heavens were a book she has been studying her entire life.</p>
                        <p>She carries burn scars on her hands, the signature of alien weaponry, and a grief that she wears with quiet dignity. Her husband is gone. Her son died in her arms. The road has become her home and the stars her family. She does not believe in fate&mdash;&ldquo;If I did, I would have to believe that my son and my husband died because something in the stars willed it&rdquo;&mdash;but she believes in putting one foot in front of the other, in the practical magic of survival.</p>
                        <p>When she meets a certain blind traveler on the road, Anjari becomes the first person in years to hear the full truth about what is coming. Her reaction&mdash;equal parts awe, terror, and stubborn hope&mdash;mirrors what every reader will feel.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/anjari-outfit.webp" alt="Anjari — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

            <div class="separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

            <!-- BABA -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">Baba</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">A young tracker with old eyes, reading the wasteland like a native tongue</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/baba-pose.webp" alt="Baba — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>Her real name is Barbera, but she couldn&rsquo;t say it as a child, so Baba it became and Baba it remains. She grew up on the terrain between Solos and the gorge, learning to track from her father, reading the earth and sky without thinking&mdash;the accumulated fluency of a life spent mastering a single language. She is young, but the wasteland ages people past their years, and her eyes carry a watchfulness that belongs to a woman twice her age.</p>
                        <p>Baba dreams of leading her own trade caravan someday, of becoming a Trade Master who memorizes the routes and guides caravans by dead reckoning across landscapes where a wrong turn means death. She reads approaching storms by smell, identifies terrain by feel, and knows which paths lead to safety and which lead to Naomi&rsquo;s crew of pirates known as the Bullriders.</p>
                        <p>Her grandfather served under the old monarch. Her knowledge of the wasteland&rsquo;s dangers is encyclopedic. And when she encounters a certain group of strangers struggling back from the gorge, she sees something in them&mdash;particularly in the quiet young man with the braids and the heavy-lidded eyes&mdash;that makes her want to help.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/baba-outfit.webp" alt="Baba — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

        </section><!-- end region: The Wasteland & The Spice Road -->

        <div class="region-separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

        <!-- ==============================
             REGION 3: THE REBEL BUNKER
             ============================== -->
        <section class="region-section">
            <h2 class="region-header">The Rebel Bunker</h2>
            <p class="region-tagline">Seven floors underground, where hope is rationed like water</p>
            <div class="region-image-wrapper">
                <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/region-bunker.webp" alt="The Rebel Bunker — A hidden underground stronghold seven floors deep" loading="lazy">
            </div>
            <div class="region-text">
                <p>No one knows exactly where the bunker is&mdash;its inhabitants are brought there blindfolded, and its thick concrete walls shield it from the tracking signals that have betrayed every other refuge. Seven floors deep, connected by stairs, the bunker is part military base, part refugee camp, and part last stand. It houses the malnourished, the orphaned, the escaped, and the stubbornly alive&mdash;survivors who were never meant to be an army but who are becoming one anyway.</p>
                <p>The walls are lined with hand-drawn maps sketched in red charcoal, marking the advancing boundaries of alien vegetation. The boundaries are closer than anyone expected. Food is rationed. Weapons are sharpened. Training happens in corridors too narrow for proper combat drills. There are birthing areas&mdash;only two still functional&mdash;because even at the end of the world, children are born, and someone has to deliver them.</p>
                <p>The bunker runs on logistics, willpower, and the stubborn refusal to accept that humanity&rsquo;s time is up. It is not a place of comfort. It is a place of purpose. And for the ragged band of fighters who call it home, purpose is enough.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- PO -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">Po</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">A philosopher who fights like water and leads like stone</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/po-pose.webp" alt="Po — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>Before the Marines arrived, before the armies formed, there was Po&mdash;standing at the front of a ragged band of survivors with nothing but breathing techniques and a Buddhist&rsquo;s calm. His qigong meditation centers him in the chaos of combat. His training begins not with weapons but with breath. &ldquo;First you will learn how to breathe,&rdquo; he tells his students. &ldquo;If you can&rsquo;t breathe, you can&rsquo;t fight.&rdquo;</p>
                        <p>Po&rsquo;s philosophy is deceptively simple: be present, be honest, be ready. &ldquo;If the sun is shining and my enemy says so, I will agree,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;My allegiance is with the truth.&rdquo; But beneath that stillness lies a wound that has never fully healed&mdash;a wife killed not by aliens but by another human, a betrayal that taught him that the enemy does not always look the way you expect.</p>
                        <p>When Po disappears during a critical mission, the rebels lose more than a fighter. They lose a moral compass in a world where the difference between right and wrong is rarely as clear as anyone pretends. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s okay to be scared,&rdquo; he once told them. &ldquo;We don&rsquo;t bury the scared. We bury the dead.&rdquo;</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/po-outfit.webp" alt="Po — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

            <div class="separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

            <!-- WAX GRIFFIN -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">Wax Griffin</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">The man who keeps the lights on while everyone else saves the world</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/wax-pose.webp" alt="Wax Griffin — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>Every rebellion needs someone who counts the ammunition, rations the water, and stares at hand-drawn maps until the red charcoal lines blur into nightmares. Wax Griffin is that person. As administrator of the rebel bunker, he manages the impossible logistics of sheltering, feeding, and arming a population of survivors who were never meant to be an army.</p>
                        <p>Wax hasn&rsquo;t slept in days. The maps on his wall show the known boundaries of alien growth sketched in red, and the boundaries are closer than anyone expected. &ldquo;Two years,&rdquo; he tells them. &ldquo;Maybe two.&rdquo; He says it the way a man reads a death sentence&mdash;not with drama, but with the exhausted precision of someone who has checked the numbers three times and knows they won&rsquo;t change.</p>
                        <p>He is the first to say what everyone is thinking: there isn&rsquo;t much time, and there are no reinforcements coming. The war will be fought with what they have. And what they have starts with Wax, alone in a corridor, staring at a map, wondering if it&rsquo;s enough.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/wax-outfit.webp" alt="Wax Griffin — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

            <div class="separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

            <!-- DADE -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">Dade</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">A drunk, a gambler, and the last person you want training you&mdash;unless you want to survive</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/dade-pose.webp" alt="Dade — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>Dade mangles proverbs. He calls women &ldquo;Bambi&rsquo;s.&rdquo; He drinks too much, bets on everything, and carries himself with the insufferable swagger of a man who believes, against all available evidence, that he is God&rsquo;s gift to the wasteland. He is, by most accounts, completely insufferable.</p>
                        <p>He is also terrifyingly good at killing things.</p>
                        <p>Dade&rsquo;s fighting philosophy is built on misdirection&mdash;&ldquo;Make your enemy look at something else, then attack&rdquo;&mdash;and his training methods are as brutal as they are effective. He doesn&rsquo;t coddle his students. He doesn&rsquo;t inspire them with speeches about hope and destiny. He teaches them to survive by making their training nearly as dangerous as the real thing. His constant sparring with Rensa produces moments of genuine comedy in an otherwise grim world, their insults escalating into something that looks, from certain angles, almost like affection. He may have &ldquo;GOOD LUCK&rdquo; tattooed across his knuckles. He will need it.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/dade-outfit.webp" alt="Dade — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

            <div class="separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

            <!-- RENSA -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">Rensa</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">A crowbar, a sharp tongue, and absolutely no chill</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/rensa-pose.webp" alt="Rensa — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>Born into the demimonde, motherless young, fatherless always, Rensa learned to fight by keeping predators off her back in the back alleys of a world that offered no safety nets. She is gamine and wiry, dark-skinned and green-eyed, with a mop of matted hair and a mouth that could strip paint. Her weapon of choice is a crowbar, which she notes is a useful tool that serves several purposes beyond caving in skulls.</p>
                        <p>Rensa is chaos incarnate&mdash;brutal, unpredictable, and utterly without pretense. She extracts intelligence from brothels and criminal dens that more respectable operatives could never access, navigating the underworld with the ease of someone who has never known any other world. Her constant verbal warfare with Dade masks a genuine bond forged in shared combat and training sessions that leave both of them bloodied.</p>
                        <p>Her loyalty, once earned, runs deeper than her caustic exterior suggests. But earning it requires surviving her first&mdash;and Rensa has a saying about the quickest way to a man&rsquo;s heart that involves a bone saw.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/rensa-outfit.webp" alt="Rensa — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

        </section><!-- end region: The Rebel Bunker -->

        <div class="region-separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

        <!-- ==============================
             REGION 4: SID MANTELIS
             ============================== -->
        <section class="region-section">
            <h2 class="region-header">Sid Mantelis</h2>
            <p class="region-tagline">A city of spires and masks, where beauty conceals something far darker</p>
            <div class="region-image-wrapper">
                <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/region-sidmantelis.webp" alt="Sid Mantelis — The last great domed city on Earth" loading="lazy">
            </div>
            <div class="region-text">
                <p>Beneath its shimmering dome&mdash;a cordon of electromagnetic nanoparticles that blocks the poisoned air and alien spores&mdash;Sid Mantelis is the last great city on Earth. Thirty-five thousand souls live within its walls, breathing clean air, walking through elaborate parks filled with carved topiary animals, worshipping at cathedrals whose spires pierce an oxygen-rich sky. At night the dome bathes the city in sepia light, casting soft shadows across a pastoral landscape that feels like a memory of the world that was. It is, by any measure, a monument to human achievement in times of great difficulty.</p>
                <p>It is also a prison.</p>
                <p>The Church of Omaha governs everything within the dome. An animistic faith built on the worship of Earth&rsquo;s lost mammals&mdash;creatures revered as aspects of human nature in a world where the animals themselves are extinct&mdash;the Church demands absolute obedience in exchange for safety. The clergy wear ceremonial animal masks called personas, their identities hidden, their authority absolute. &ldquo;No human elevated above another,&rdquo; the scripture says. The Chief Cleric decides what the scripture means. Citizens who enter Sid Mantelis take a vow never to leave. Weekly services are mandatory. Dissent is not tolerated. And the prophets&mdash;those who speak of futures the Church has not approved&mdash;are silenced.</p>
                <p>The city is beautiful. The robes are gorgeous. The gold filigree gleams. But there are those who have begun to wonder what the beauty is hiding&mdash;and whether the price of safety has already grown too high.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- CYGNUS -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">Cygnus &mdash; The Chief Cleric</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">The voice of God in a city that worships beasts</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/cygnus-pose.webp" alt="Cygnus — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>Behind the lion persona&mdash;the ceremonial mask that conceals the Chief Cleric&rsquo;s identity from the faithful&mdash;stands a figure known only by his clerical aspect: Cygnus, the Swan. He ascended to the highest seat of the Church of Life through the ritual of Annunciation, assuming command of Sid Mantelis and its population of over thirty-five thousand souls sheltered beneath the great dome.</p>
                        <p>The Church of Life is an animistic faith built on the worship of Earth&rsquo;s lost mammals&mdash;creatures memorialized in carved topiary gardens and ceremonial masks, revered as aspects of human nature in a world where the animals themselves are extinct. The clergy live sequestered behind their personas, theoretically equal, theoretically anonymous. &ldquo;No human elevated above another,&rdquo; the scripture says. The Chief Cleric decides what the scripture means.</p>
                        <p>Cygnus wasted no time consolidating power. He has purged dissenters, silenced the prophets, and begun reshaping the faith to serve purposes the original founders never intended. &ldquo;Religion is simple,&rdquo; he declares. &ldquo;What God wants is simple. He wants obedience.&rdquo; But there are those within Sid Mantelis who suspect that the face behind the mask holds secrets far stranger than mere ambition&mdash;secrets about what the Chief Cleric truly is and whom he truly serves.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/cygnus-outfit.webp" alt="Cygnus — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

            <div class="separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

            <!-- TRINIDAD -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">Trinidad</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">A blind woman who sees more than anyone alive</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/trinidad-pose.webp" alt="Trinidad — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>They call her &ldquo;Raven&rdquo; in the halls of Sid Mantelis, and they say it with fear. Trinidad possesses the gift&mdash;or the curse&mdash;of prophetic vision. Her pale green eyes are clouded by blindness, but they perceive things no sighted person can: the threads of fate, the architecture of what has been and what will be, the hidden patterns that connect past and future like the warp and weft of a single cloth.</p>
                        <p>She was once advisor to a monarch. She foretold his death. She escaped execution by the skin of her teeth and the loyalty of an unlikely guardian. Now she walks the Spice Road with a prophecy burning in her chest&mdash;words about a child who will save the barren Earth, about a hero who will hold &ldquo;the alien light&rdquo;&mdash;searching for the strangers she has seen in her visions, the ones who will either fulfill the prophecy or die trying.</p>
                        <p>Trinidad&rsquo;s powers are growing. The visions come more frequently, more vividly, pressing against the boundaries of what her body can contain. Something is changing in her. Something is coming. And the woman she is now may not be the woman she becomes.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/trinidad-outfit.webp" alt="Trinidad &amp; Riley — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

            <div class="separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

            <!-- RILEY -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">Riley</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">A mute boy who speaks in pictures and sees for the blind</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/riley-pose.webp" alt="Riley — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>Riley does not speak. Whether he cannot or will not, no one is entirely sure. But silence, for Riley, is not absence&mdash;it is a different kind of language. He communicates through images projected directly into Trinidad&rsquo;s mind: a question mark when he&rsquo;s confused, a pair of binoculars when she asks him to look, a lion when danger approaches. She provides him with words; he provides her with sight. Together they form something greater than either could be alone.</p>
                        <p>His clerical aspect&mdash;the Turtle&mdash;was assigned by those who mistook his silence for slowness. They were wrong. Riley&rsquo;s loyalty to Trinidad is absolute, the fierce devotion of someone who has found the one person in the world who truly understands him. He hears everything. He sees everything. And through the bond they share, so does she.</p>
                        <p>Small and watchful, with large brown eyes that scan the horizon with an alertness far beyond his years, Riley is easy to underestimate. That is, perhaps, exactly what keeps them both alive.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <div class="separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

            <!-- SENTINELLA -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">Sentinella</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">The holy guard of Sid Mantelis, armed with halberds and divided loyalties</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/sentinella-pose.webp" alt="Sentinella — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>The Sentinella are the ceremonial and military guard of the Church of Life&mdash;over two thousand strong, armored in faith and armed with halberds, the long-shafted bladed weapons of the holy order. They enforce the Chief Cleric&rsquo;s will, guard the dome&rsquo;s gates, and maintain order among a population that has traded freedom for safety. Each Sentinella bears an animal aspect, their identity subsumed into the church&rsquo;s mythology: Urso the Bear, Oso the Ox, Gammon the Pig, Boz the Aurochs.</p>
                        <p>But the masks that preserve anonymity also conceal conscience. Not every guard believes what they are ordered to enforce. Some carry private doubts beneath their personas, torn between duty to the faith and loyalty to something older and less easily defined&mdash;truth, perhaps, or justice, or simply the stubborn conviction that what they are being asked to do is wrong.</p>
                        <p>When the moment comes to choose&mdash;obedience or rebellion, mask or face&mdash;the Sentinella will fracture. And the side each one falls on may determine whether Sid Mantelis endures or burns.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/sentinella-outfit.webp" alt="Sentinella — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

        </section><!-- end region: Sid Mantelis -->

        <div class="region-separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

        <!-- ==============================
             REGION 5: THE FREE CITY OF SOLOS
             ============================== -->
        <section class="region-section">
            <h2 class="region-header">The Free City of Solos</h2>
            <p class="region-tagline">Where everything has a price and nothing is forbidden</p>
            <div class="region-image-wrapper">
                <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/region-solos.webp" alt="The Free City of Solos — A bustling underground metropolis lit by ten thousand candles" loading="lazy">
            </div>
            <div class="region-text">
                <p>From the surface, you would never know it exists. The buildings above are boarded up, covered in debris and sagebrush, indistinguishable from the rocky terrain around them. This is by design. Solos has survived for three centuries by being invisible.</p>
                <p>Below ground, it is a different world entirely. Built in abandoned subway tunnels, parking garages, and sewer systems, Solos is a bustling underground metropolis lit by ten thousand candles. Steam power drives its machinery. Clockwork weapons hang in market stalls beside baskets woven by some of the finest artisans left alive. The air smells of ramen broth and candle wax and the particular kind of danger that comes from a city with no laws and six gangs maintaining order through mutual threat. Barter coins made of pig iron change hands over dried herbs sold by the finger, snakeskin leather, and information worth more than either.</p>
                <p>Six gangs carve up the underground economy: arms dealers, pit fighters, smugglers, merchants, mechanics, and the oldest profession. They compete, they cooperate, they occasionally kill each other&mdash;but the city endures because everyone understands the same unspoken rule: Solos survives by being useful to everyone and loyal to no one.</p>
                <p>The contrast with Sid Mantelis is deliberate and thematic. Sid Mantelis hides its evil behind the veil of religion and government, committing atrocities through deception. Solos is full of common criminals in plain view. &ldquo;At least with thieves,&rdquo; someone observes, &ldquo;you know what to expect.&rdquo; In a world where institutional evil wears golden robes, there is something almost refreshing about a city that is honest about being dishonest.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- IDEO GOKU -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">Ideo Goku</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">A shinobi&rsquo;s daughter with her father&rsquo;s blades and a gift for making things explode</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/ideo-pose.webp" alt="Ideo Goku — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>Ideo comes from the Free City of Solos, the lawless underground metropolis where everything has a price and nothing is forbidden. Her father, Hong Goku, runs the legendary Red Fin House of Ramen and taught her the ways of the shinobi&mdash;the Sengoku-era traditions of stealth, sabotage, and silent killing. Her mother, Sun-Yi, is a healer who knows every medicinal herb that still grows in the poisoned earth. Between them, they raised a woman equally comfortable assembling an explosive charge and identifying a healing root by smell.</p>
                        <p>Ideo left Solos seven years ago, carrying her family&rsquo;s martial traditions into the wider wasteland. When the rebels need weapons, medicine, and allies, it is Ideo who suggests the dangerous journey back to the underground city she once called home. Her knowledge of Solos&rsquo;s six rival gangs&mdash;she counts six where others count only five&mdash;makes her invaluable. Her expertise in explosives engineering makes her indispensable.</p>
                        <p>But the road back to Solos passes through alien gardens where the air itself is poison, and homecomings in the wasteland rarely go the way anyone plans.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/ideo-outfit.webp" alt="Ideo Goku — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

            <div class="separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

            <!-- SUN-YI GOKU -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">Sun-Yi Goku</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">A healer who tends what the wasteland breaks</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/sunyi-pose.webp" alt="Sun-Yi Goku — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>In the underground city of Solos, where everything has a price and violence is the primary currency, Sun-Yi Goku tends her garden of medicinal herbs and heals the wounded who find their way to the Goku household. She is Ideo&rsquo;s mother and Hong&rsquo;s wife, the quiet center of a family that balances martial tradition with the gentler art of keeping people alive.</p>
                        <p>Sun-Yi knows every root and leaf that still grows in the poisoned earth&mdash;which ones reduce fever, which ones clean wounds, which ones ease the pain of injuries too severe for anything else. In a world without hospitals, without antibiotics, without the medical infrastructure that the old civilization took for granted, a healer who knows her herbs is worth more than a dozen soldiers.</p>
                        <p>She and Hong built something rare in Solos: a home. A place where ramen steams in bowls and wayward rebels are welcomed with hugs and warm handshakes. That kind of warmth, in a world this cold, is its own form of resistance.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/sunyi-outfit.webp" alt="Sun-Yi Goku — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

            <div class="separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

            <!-- GUNTHER -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">Gunther</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">A crime lord who mistakes his proximity to death for poetry</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/gunther-pose.webp" alt="Gunther — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>Gunther runs the fighting pits of Solos, the bloodsport arenas where the underground city&rsquo;s appetite for violence finds its purest expression. He leads the Hotheads&mdash;also called the Reds&mdash;one of six gangs that maintain the city&rsquo;s rough semblance of order through mutual threat and competing ambition. He fancies himself a philosopher of combat, a connoisseur of human struggle, a man who appreciates the artistry of a well-thrown punch.</p>
                        <p>He is none of these things. Gunther is a sociopath who has learned to dress his appetites in language borrowed from better men. &ldquo;Cards can be marked,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;Dice can be loaded. But fighting&mdash;people will always want fighting.&rdquo; He surveys the damage to his arena not with grief but with arithmetic, tallying costs, calculating returns, already scheming how to rebuild something profitable from the wreckage.</p>
                        <p>In a city where honesty about being dishonest is considered a virtue, Gunther is the closest thing to an honest man. That should tell you everything about Solos.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/gunther-outfit.webp" alt="Gunther — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

        </section><!-- end region: The Free City of Solos -->

        <div class="region-separator"><span class="diamond"></span></div>

        <!-- ==============================
             REGION 6: THE ALIENS
             ============================== -->
        <section class="region-section">
            <h2 class="region-header">The Aliens</h2>
            <p class="region-tagline">They came after humanity fell &mdash; and they are not what they seem</p>
            <div class="region-image-wrapper">
                <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/region-aliens.webp" alt="The Aliens — The towering Mogglogians who descended after the Dark Epoch" loading="lazy">
            </div>
            <div class="region-text">
                <p>The creatures arrived during the Dark Epoch&mdash;or rather, after it. When Earth&rsquo;s magnetic reversal had already shattered civilization, when billions had died from famine and exposure and war, when humanity was nothing more than scattered survivors huddling in the ruins of their own world&mdash;that is when they descended. They tend vast gardens of alien flora that consume nitrogen and release argon, slowly transforming Earth&rsquo;s atmosphere into something hostile to every native living thing. They run slave camps. They hunt. They are nine-to-ten-foot nightmares of horn and claw and serrated teeth, and for three centuries they have been the reason humanity sleeps underground and travels in disguise.</p>
                <p>Humans call them Sky Reapers. Ajnabiun. Usurpers. Creatures. Beasts. Monsters.</p>
                <p>They call themselves Mogglogians&mdash;a word that is not from any human language.</p>
                <p>But the Mogglogians share something unexpected with the species they terrorize: Earth DNA. The same amino acids, the same proteins, the same blood types. They are not visitors from a distant star. They are something stranger, something closer to home, and the truth of what they are&mdash;and who they serve&mdash;is one of Metalstar&rsquo;s deepest mysteries. To say more would be to unravel threads that the story itself is still weaving.</p>
                <p>Not everything that looks like a monster is one. And not every enemy knows it is enslaved.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- THE MOGGLOGIANS -->
            <section class="character-entry">
                <h2 class="character-name">The Mogglogians</h2>
                <p class="character-tagline">The giants who reap the sky&mdash;but whose story is more complicated than anyone knows</p>
                <div class="character-body">
                    <div class="pose-image-wrapper">
                        <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/mogglogian-pose.webp" alt="Mogglogian — Pose" loading="lazy">
                    </div>
                    <div class="character-text">
                        <p>Humans call them Sky Reapers, or simply <em>the creatures</em>&mdash;nine-to-ten-foot terrors with barrel chests, clawed fingers, horns, and multiple rows of serrated teeth set above thick, elephant-like legs. They tend the alien gardens that are slowly choking Earth&rsquo;s atmosphere. They run the slave camps. They descend from the sky in ships that blot out what little sun remains. For three centuries, they have been humanity&rsquo;s nightmare given flesh.</p>
                        <p>But the Mogglogians&mdash;the name they use for themselves&mdash;share something unexpected with the species they terrorize: Earth DNA. The same amino acids, the same proteins, the same blood types. They are not visitors from a distant star. They are something far stranger, far closer to home, and far more tragic than the simple monsters humanity has made them out to be.</p>
                        <p>John D&rsquo;arby is the first to see it. &ldquo;I see aspects of all Earth&rsquo;s creatures in these beasts,&rdquo; he says, studying them with the eyes of a hunter who respects his prey. The truth of what the Mogglogians are, where they came from, and <em>who controls them</em> is one of Metalstar&rsquo;s deepest mysteries&mdash;and its answer will reshape every assumption about who the real enemy is.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="outfit-image-wrapper">
                    <img src="/assets/images/luminarium/mogglogian-outfit.webp" alt="Mogglogian — Outfit Sheet" loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </section>

        </section><!-- end region: The Aliens -->

        <!-- Closing -->
        <p class="luminarium-closing"><em>These are the faces of the 24th century. Each carries secrets that will reshape your understanding of their world&mdash;and perhaps your own. Their full stories unfold in</em> <strong>Metalstar</strong>.</p>

    </div>

